    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm working on an embedded c++ project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow memory leak. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually runs out of available ram and crashes. i don't see any obvious missing deletes in my main loop. how should i go about systematically finding where the leak is happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak in an embedded C++ system, especially one running for hours, is a classic, frustrating problem. You'll need to track the memory allocation patterns, which is much trickier than a simple heap leak in a desktop application. Try to use a memory profiling tool, if your toolchain allows it, or implement custom tracking macros around `new` and `delete` to count allocations and track their call stacks. If you can't use a sophisticated profiler, you might need to instrument your code to log the size and location of every allocation, which is a bit more manual, but it's the only way to catch the sneaky little memory hogs. Remember, sometimes the leak isn't a missing `delete`, but rather an object being held onto by a static pointer or a global cache that never gets cleared.",
      "source": "target",
