    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A \"glorp-sized\" allocation, in the context of my previous comment, is just a colorful way of describing a small, insignificant-looking chunk of memory—something that seems too tiny to matter on its own. It's not a formal engineering term, but it describes the insidious nature of the problem! Imagine a tiny, barely noticeable pile of pebbles that, when you gather enough of them, can build a wall strong enough to block a whole path. These small allocations are like those tiny, persistent pebbles.\n\nThese tiny allocations are often the trickiest because they don't trigger the alarms you set for large memory dumps. They are the digital equivalent of a tiny, persistent, low-grade annoyance that eventually becomes a massive, overwhelming problem. It's just as likely that a thousand tiny, forgotten pointers are holding onto a few bytes each, leading to a total system failure, as it is that one massive, obvious leak.",
      "source": "target",
